Proposal

Abstract
This project focuses on developing a proof of concept that exists out of two parts. 
1. A standardized method to define a set of decentralized agents that can exchange messages and data, and also send, accept and reject tasks. 
2. A JavaScript package that makes a developer able to instantiate these agents within their web apps, to let them connect to other agents and to expose the functionality of these web apps as the agent’s capabilities.


Proposed solution
We build a PoC for a minimal, portable standard for turning any JavaScript based web app into an agent that can participate in decentralized data exchange, messaging, streaming and task sharing. In order to do this, we want to develop an open source function package that:
    • helps developers turn their application into an agent that operates in a user defined decentralized agent network
    • where data is only shared on terms of the users or agents, without need for a central server

In the description below we offer examples of existing technologies that we could use for functionalities that we think we should not develop ourselves. In order to stay flexible during development, we need to allow ourselves to divert to alternative pieces of software if we find that more appropriate for our goals. The technologies suggested should therefore be understood as examples or candidate solutions, without any commitment in this stage.\
    • Agent definition and information exchange (e.g. A2A protocol)
    • Networking: while we strive to implement compatibility with peer-to-peer connectivity, for this PoC we want to use NKN (New Kind of Network), a blockchain solution that organizes peer-to-peer connectivity, as this already implements a lot of the functionality we need
    • Storage: for now the storage will be done in local memory (while for the future we see especially high potential in compatibility with Solid Pods)
New Functionality
The main functionality we want to develop, consists of two parts:
    1. A portable file in which the user can define:
        ◦ Data source connections + authentication methods
        ◦ Addresses for agent peers / addresses for agent peer discovery platforms
        ◦ Agent network groups: group membership can influence discoverability for other agents, the exposure of peers and connections and they can be used to manage permissions

    2. A portable package that a developer can use to turn an app into one or more agents that are capable of:
        ◦ Connecting
            ▪ connecting to data sources
            ▪ connecting to agent peers
        ◦ Discovery
            ▪ discovering peers
            ▪ exposing their capabilities to peers (e.g. connections and app functions)
        ◦ Communicating
            ▪ messaging
            ▪ exchanging data (requests) with peers
            ▪ submit + accept/reject tasks to the network

    3. In order to integrate the agent with the app, a developer must be able to redefine its app functions as agent capabilities. For this we want to develop a (for now JavaScript) package that can be imported by developers which provides ways to:
        ◦ load an agent defined by the user
        ◦ initialize an agent based on the properties file
        ◦ define app-functions as agent capabilities
        ◦ map agent task parameters to function arguments
This way, users can flexibly connect to their agent network from different places, while developers can create apps that can add new functionality to this network.

Technical approach

All parts will be made public under the MIT-license.

    1. Design for Agents Properties File
This could be an encrypted yaml or json file that contains:
- agent ID's
- pointer to key/passwords/token vault
- list of connections to:
- db's
- api's
- networks
- other agent IDs
- etc
- agent group ID’s
- optional: define roles to organize these connections/credentials/groups
- optional: list of approved app-IDs (or link to list)
- permissions
- for sharing capabilities to group members
- for sharing peers to group members

    2. Optional: Simple web app for creating agent properties file
    • Easy to make, useful for testing

    3. Agent loading package
    1. Runtime
        1. load agent properties file
        2. initialize agent based on the file (e.g. A2A protocol)
        3. send messages to other agents
        4. exchange data with other agents
        5. send tasks to the network
    2. Integration functions for application
        1. connect app functions to agent capabilities
        2. connect task parameters to function arguments
    3. Networking
        1. connect to other devices (e.g. New Kind of Network (NKN), in the future preferably p2p technology such as WebRTC)
        2. discover given agents on connected devices
        3. discover new agents by peer discovery
    4. Coordination
        1. local cache of known agents and capabilities
        2. task-capability matcher
        3. procedure for accepting/rejecting a task from the network


